div.p: Recommendation: Generational GC with compaction
Cause: Alternating alloc/free Impact: High external fragmentation Solution: Compaction or bump allocator
Cause: Objects allocated at start Impact: Wasted space at end Solution: Bump pointer allocation
Cause: Free blocks too small Impact: Allocation failures Solution: Segregated free lists
Request: alloc(256KB) Total Free: 256 KB Largest Block: 128 KB Result: ALLOCATION FAILS
Why? No single contiguous block large enough
Request: alloc(128KB) Total Free: 256 KB Largest Block: 64 KB Result: ALLOCATION FAILS
Why? All free blocks too small
[A][][B][][C][] alloc(256KB) fails
[A][B][C][] alloc(256KB) succeeds
Cost: O(n) time to move objects
Approach: Move live objects together
When to use: Low fragmentation tolerance
Approach: Separate free lists by size class
When to use: Predictable object sizes
Approach: Choose smallest sufficient block
When to use: Memory-constrained systems
Approach: Separate young/old objects
When to use: Most applications
Without compaction: Grows to 80-90% With compaction: Stays below 20%

ul.li:
Each request allocates:
10 small objects (16-64 bytes)
2 medium objects (256-512 bytes)
1 large object (4-8 KB)
